<div class="comment"><div class="commtext c00">Read-only TOML support is in the standard library since Python 3.11, though. And it&#x27;s based on an easily obtained third-party package (<a href="https:&#x2F;&#x2F;pypi.org&#x2F;project&#x2F;tomli&#x2F;" rel="nofollow">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;pypi.org&#x2F;project&#x2F;tomli&#x2F;</a>).<p>(If you want to <i>write</i> TOML, or do other advanced things such as preserving comments and exact structure from the original file, you&#x27;ll want tomlkit instead. Note that it&#x27;s much less performant.)</div><div class="reply"><p><font size="1"><u><a href="reply?id=44371416&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D44369388%2344371416" rel="nofollow">reply</a></u></font></div></div></td></tr>
